Residents of a village in northern India rode a tigress on a tractor that had previously stabbed one man, officials said Monday.
Forest steward Mahavir Kaujlagi (Mahavir Kaujlagi) said that when the tigress stabbed a man who worked in the fields late Sunday, the villagers surrounded the beast and, as the female tried to escape, drove her with a tractor.
Residents say that this tigress also attacked and insured one young man about 10 days ago.
The village in question is located in the Dudhwa Tiger Reserve in Lakhympur Kher district, about 250 km southeast of Laknau, the capital of the state of Uttar Pradesh.
Galabyte tigers in protected areas is prohibited.
The reserve's director, Ramesh Pandey, said the case would be reported to police under the Wildlife Protection Act.
In April, in the Nighasan district of Uttar Pradesh state, villagers beat another tiger; he suffered serious injuries.
The tiger is the national animal of India; according to the Wildlife Protection Act, tigers are considered an endangered species.
Last year's government figures show that for the past three years, at least one person has been killed daily in clashes with wild tigers or elephants.
Human conflicts with tigers have been gradually increasing since the 8th, when India launched a program to protect tigers, according to which reserves were established in national parks, and the gallicing of large cats began to be considered a crime.
While the methods of counting tigers have changed, the censuses would indicate that the then population of about 1,800 tigers grew to 2,226 individuals in 2014.
It is proposed that cats and dogs should be marked with microchips on a mandatory basis
Kęstutis Mažeika, Chairman of the Environmental Protection Committee of the Seimas, together with other members of the Seimas, has registered amendments to the Law on the Welfare and Protection of Animals, which propose the mandatory marking of cats and dogs with subcutaneous microchips.
"We propose that cats and dogs should be marked with subcutaneous microchips, and their registration and marking should be organized by local municipalities, the Ministry of Agriculture and the State Food and Veterinary Service.
In 2019, all dogs will be marked free of charge with state funds, and in 2020 - also cats, so residents will not be worried and the costs will be covered by specially provided state funding," said Kęstutis Mažeika, chairman of the Seimas Committee on Environmental Protection.
The amendments to the law are aimed at solving the systematic need for the marking of pets.
It is hoped that this will help to avoid problems caused by irresponsible animal breeders, illegal multipliers or sellers.
It is tentatively estimated that all animal owners will be compensated during the transitional period on the basis of the expected average price of the microchip and the service, which will amount to about 5 euros.
The total cost of marking all pets can reach up to $ 6 million. Euro.
It is planned that the need for these funds will be distributed over three years and will amount to EUR 2 million annually. Euro.
It is planned that the funds for the labeling programs will be allocated through the Special Program for the Support of Municipal Environmental Protection, whose revenues will increase significantly this year due to increased taxes on natural resources and the redistribution of funds.
Municipalities will be able to use these funds not only for the marking of cats and dogs, but also for castration and other programs.
According to K. Mažeika, the practice of mandatory labelling is common in almost all European Union countries, which allows you to protect both the animals themselves (because the lost ones can easily be returned to the owners), and saves the time of the animal breeders themselves, when the search for a runaway and lost pet has to be spent a lot of time and money.
In addition, EU legislation stipulates that travel is only possible with tagged pets.
At the same time, labeling obliges you to responsibly take care of the animal throughout its life.
The previous proposals for mandatory labelling have met with resistance, as the relevant programmes have been proposed to be funded by the population.
"The model now being put forward should avoid this criticism, since animal protection is proposed to be financed by increased revenues in the environmental support program and giving the right to label not only to veterinarians, but also to public figures, i.e. persons of animal care institutions who have taken special courses at the Academy of Veterinary Medicine," the authors of the project say.
The draft law was registered by a group of Seimas members representing different political groups in the Seimas - Kęstutis Mažeika, Algimantas Dumbrava, Eugenijus Gentvilas, Edmundas Pupinis, Rimas Andrikis, Antanas Vinkus and others.
