Restrictions on cogeneration power-plants appealed to the Constitutional Court
The opposition in the Seimas, as promised, appealed to the Constitutional Court (KT) against the decision of the ruling parties to adopt a law on the possibility of stopping the construction of waste incineration plants.
On Tuesday, the opposition faction of the Homeland Union-Lithuanian Christian Democrats (TS-LKD) in the Seimas reported that a group of Seimas members had appealed to the KT to investigate the conformity of the amendments to the Law on Waste Management adopted by the rulers with the Constitution.
"Parliamentarians emphasize that the provisions of the law are aimed at questioning the projects of waste incinerators already underway, entrusting the Government with the task of imposing new restrictions (a distance of 20 km from the residential area) until the entry into force of the law for waste incineration plants that have begun to be built in Vilnius and Kaunas," the report reads.
'Parliamentarians point out that, in view of the way in which the law formulates the prohibition on the construction of objects of national importance for waste management (i.e. the distance is determined and the concept of a 'residential area' is defined), it must be concluded that this prohibition disproportionately limits or even negates the very essence of the right to carry out economic activities related to the incineration of waste for the production of energy, since the established criteria are formulated in such a way that, taking into account the density and distribution of the Lithuanian population in the country, it would be practically impossible to build such facilities throughout the territory of the country," it adds.
The appeal states that the law passed is contrary to the constitutional principle of the rule of law.
"The CT has repeatedly stated that the legislation does not apply to those legal facts and consequences that occurred before the entry into force of the newly adopted legislation.
In this case, the Government is empowered to apply the law retroactively on the basis of an indeterminate criterion.
The introduction of such a legal regulation violates the constitutional principles of legal certainty, legal certainty, protection of legitimate expectations, and therefore the constitutional principle of the rule of law," the appeal states.
It also notes that large financial investments have already been made in the projects of Vilnius and Kaunas cogeneration power-plants.
If the ongoing projects were suspended, the state would suffer not only hundreds of billions of financial losses, huge losses would also be suffered by Lithuanian residents - heating prices would increase, and environmental pollution would increase due to the growing amount of waste disposal in landfills.
The appeal to the KT was signed by members from the Seimas TS-LKD, the Liberal Movement, the Social Democratic groups and algirdas Butkevičius, deputy dean of the ruling Social Democratic Labour Group.
A couple of weeks ago, the Seimas managed to garner 71 votes by the ruling parties in order to reject the veto of president Dalia Grybauskaitė's veto of the adopted amendments to the Law on Waste Management, which provide for the right of the Government to suspend the construction of cogeneration power-plants that had already begun, and also established a "quarantine" zone of 20 km from residential areas for the construction of such power plants.
Amendments to the law re-adopted by the Seimas will take effect from 1 January 2019. True, the rulers are already proposing to abandon the restriction of 20 km.
It is planned to consider this proposal at the autumn session of the Seimas.
However, there are no plans to waive the Government's right to suspend projects that have already begun.
Kt will deal with this case in order - no earlier than a year later.
