The cause of the lion air plane crash revealed: relatives of those killed are angry
Black box data from indonesia's crashed Lion Air liner shows that a speedometer malfunction occurred during at least its last four flights, investigators said Monday.
Soerjanto Tjahjono, chairman of the National Transport Security Committee (NTSC), said a similar bug occurred during the plane's last four flights, including the fateful one when the liner crashed in the Java Sea on October 29 immediately after taking off from Jakarta.
All 189 people on board were killed in this crash.
Many media outlets reported problems during the previous flight of the Boeing 737 MAX 8 plane from Denpasar to the Indonesian capital.
"When we opened the black box - yes, in fact, the technical problem was the speed in the air, in other words, the speed of the plane," Mr Tjahjono said during a press conference.
"The black box data showed that during the two flights before the Denpasar-Jakarta flight, there was also the same problem," he added.
"There are a lot of rumors circulating on social media.
Now we want to clarify that in the black box (data remained) about four flights during which there were problems with the air velocity meter," the NTSK chief said.
During a meeting with members of the families of the dead, Mr Tjahjono said the information from the device recording the flight data was in line with reports that its speed and altitude changed untidily as the plane took off on the last flight.
Search teams have yet to find a second black box recording conversations in the cockpit of pilots.
Lion Air indicated that when a technical failure was detected during the flight from Bali to Jakarta, it was repaired in accordance with the manufacturer's recommendations.
One of the company's founders, Rusdi Kirana, was not invited to speak with Transport Minister Budi Karyos Sumadi, who moderated a meeting of family members with officials overseeing the search for the remains of the plane and the victims and the investigation into the crash.
However, he stood up and bowed his head when angry and grieving family members demanded that Mr Kirana, who founded Lion Air with his brother Kusnan in 1999, introduce himself.
"Lion Air was misbehaving," said one man, who introduced himself as the father of passenger Shandy Johan Ramadhan, who worked as a prosecutor on the island where the plane flew to.
"I want Mr. Rusdi Kirana and his team to pay attention," he stressed.
- Since the beginning of the crisis, Lion Air has never contacted me.
We lost our child, but Lion Air didn't show us any compassion."
After this meeting, Mr Kirana hastily left, avoiding questions from reporters.
Many families are waiting for the results of a long process of identifying the dead.
Nearly 140 corpses, loaded parts of human remains, were handed over to police medical experts.
To date, only 14 victims have been identified.
Relatives questioned why the liner, which began to be used two months ago, was allowed to fly, although during the October 28 flight from Bali to Jakarta, a breakdown occurred, which, among other things, led to the sudden decline of the plane, which frightened passengers, immediately after takeoff.
Lion Air said the glitch had been fixed.
Is it true that the problem has been solved? - the son of one of the dead asked.
- If not, the technicians concerned must be held accountable.
The law is very clear, it was not they who said that the plane was allowed to take off again.
These bad technicians must respond under the law so that plane crashes in Indonesia do not recur.
Mr Tjahjono said the large amount of small debris and the fact that the wreckage had spread over a relatively small area indicated that the liner was likely to smash into the water while flying at a very high speed.
"The plane was solid when it crashed into the sea.
It did not explode in the air, and the plane's engines, when it touched the water, acted at high revs - this is indicated by all the broken turbine blades," the official explained.
The crash of the Lion Air liner is the worst aviation disaster in Indonesia since 1997, when a Garuda plane crashed near Medan killed 234 people.
