Presidency: no artificial relief from the referendum is needed
After the Seimas approves the proposal of the rulers to lower the referendum bar for the currently more protected section of the Constitution, the president will veto the amendments, says her adviser Mindaugas Lingė.
"More than half of the population voted for the Constitution - that's the requirement.
This and its modification, especially the articles in its first section, should certainly be no less numerous .
It's easy to predict that the president would definitely veto," Dalia Grybauskaitė's domestic policy adviser told News Radio Tuesday.
He emphasized that the first section of the Constitution defines the fundamental subjects of the state - language, flag, territory, capital, state sovereignty, therefore, reducing the number of votes necessary to change these articles, according to M. Linge, would create a "negative precedent" and "open up uncontrollable risks".
"In the president's view, there is no need for any artificial facilitations, there is more need to prepare for the referendum itself, more dialogue with the people is needed," he said.
The Sejm is scheduled to vote on Tuesday to adopt an amendment to the Referendum Law.
It provides that a decision on amendments to the first and fourteenth sections of the Constitution with higher protection shall be taken if at least two-fifths of the citizens with the right to vote agree in a referendum.
Currently, articles of the first and fourteenth sections of the Constitution can be amended by referendum by more than half of all citizens with the right to vote.
Approximately 2.5 million people in Lithuania have the right to vote. citizens: half would be 1.25 million. of the electorate, two-fifths - a million voters.
This proposal was born after the Sejm in September approved the president's veto on amendments previously passed in parliament, which relaxed the requirements for the number of votes by changing Article 12 of the first section of the Constitution, which defines citizenship.
The bar for the referendum is proposed to be lowered in the run-up to the referendum on dual citizenship, which is expected to take place on May 12 and May 26 next year, when the first and second rounds of the presidential election are scheduled.
Those who emigrated after independence on March 11, 1990, cannot currently, with some exceptions, have no dual citizenship.
The Lithuanian community of the world aspires to dual citizenship, but there are fears that under the current conditions a referendum will not take place - a sufficient number of people would not come to vote.
