Balys Buračas.
Traditions and customs of Lithuanian work
Recently, it was 120 years since the birth of the famous Lithuanian photographer and cultural chronicler, ethnographer and regional researcher Balys Buračas (1897-1972) in Sidariai, Šiaulėnai county, then šiauliai governorate.
As we celebrate the 100th anniversary of the State of Lithuania, we have a great opportunity to remember how the life-filled national revival called many Lithuanian people, including the Buračus brothers - Bali, Jonas, Broniai - from the very depths of the village to engage in the fostering, meaning and preservation of our cultural traditions.
Balys Buračas, who has traveled around his native land with a camera in his hands for more than 50 years, presented a wide and realistic picture of the customs, traditions, folk art and material culture of our country.
He sought to preserve the rapidly disappearing layers of national culture and had a rare ability to realize the enduring value of the work he was doing.
In the photographs of Balys Buračas, the Lithuanian landscape, mounds, everyday life and festive environments, our people, immortalized in national costumes, decorated the pages of Lithuanian newspapers and magazines with national costumes.
This publication contains a significant part of the legacy of Bali Burač, dedicated to the description of the national customs of labor and related traditions and, most importantly, their fascinating iconography.
The published material shows not only the peculiarity and beauty of those traditions, but also the progress of our civilization over the past century, despite two world wars and a difficult occupation.
The manuscript of the book is especially rich in descriptions written by Balys Buračas of interwar Samogitia, especially Kupiškėnai, Šiaulėnai, Telšiškės, as well as the inhabitants of Aukštaitija and Dzūkija, their holidays and other traditions and customs.
Of the approximately 10000 negatives stored in museums and archives, over 400 rare, mostly hitherto unpublished, photographs have been selected for this publication, which are grouped according to selected texts.
They reflect unique aspects of ethnic culture, which are characteristic of Kupiškėnai, Dzūkai, other districts of Aukštaitija and Žemaitija.
