The Seimas approved higher fines for harmful products
The Seimas approved amendments to the Law on Product Safety, which provide that fines for violations of product safety must be increased.
The amendments were approved unanimously in the Chamber.
As Antanas Vinkus, a member of the Seimas Committee on Health Affairs, said, with regard to the new project, it is to be welcomed that the goals set are related to better protection of consumers of products.
In addition, its provisions are adapted to the requirements of the Decision of the European Parliament and of the Council.
"In my opinion, the proposed bill distributes more perfectly and specifically to all the executors involved in the supply and distribution process: manufacturers, service providers, importers, distributors and others.
As practice shows, the current system of fines does not always prevent further violations, since the subjects who have paid fines continue to commit repeated violations," said A. Vinkus.
The draft was prepared by the Ministry of Economy, after the approval of the Government, the Economic Committee of the Seimas supplemented it with its proposals.
The amendments to the law are aimed at increasing fines for violations, strengthening the protection of consumer rights, empowering market surveillance authorities and creating a clear system of supervision of product safety requirements and compliance with them.
According to the Ministry of Economy, there is currently no obligation for producers to properly label a product and thus ensure its traceability.
In addition, according to the ministry, the state control of product safety by the market surveillance authorities did not give the right to enter the territory of manufacturers and suppliers, buildings, premises, to carry out inspections, which complicates the work of the authorities.
In the ministry's view, the six-month deadline for imposing fines and warnings is too short to identify the violation, conduct an investigation and impose a fine.
Also, according to the ministry, the fines imposed are not effective enough.
Companies often repeatedly violate the requirements of the law - in 2017 alone, 14 companies did it.
The Ministry of Economy proposed to impose an obligation on manufacturers to properly label a product, thereby ensuring its traceability in order to make it easier for market surveillance authorities to identify suppliers of non-compliant products.
It is also proposed to give market surveillance authorities the right, when carrying out state control of product safety, to enter the territory, buildings, premises of economic entities that produce, place products on the market, to carry out inspections.
It is intended to increase the amounts of fines for violations of the law.
A fine of between €150 and €2,500 (now between €144 and €1,448) would be imposed on the manufacturer, importer or authorised representative who places dangerous products on the market and the distributor who has made them available on the market.
If the State Consumer Rights Protection Authority (VVTAT) or another market surveillance authority decides to prohibit the placing on the market and placing on the market of dangerous products or the provision of dangerous services, a fine of 1,000 to 5,000 (now from 868 to 4,344) euros would be imposed.
Failure to comply with the requirement to withdraw dangerous products from the market, to recall them from consumers and to destroy them would result in a fine of between EUR 2500 and EUR 6 500 (now between EUR 1 448 and EUR 5 792).
If dangerous products have caused harm to the health of the consumer, a fine of between EUR 2 500 and EUR 15 000 (now between EUR 1 448 and EUR 11584) would be imposed.
If dangerous products caused the death of a consumer, a fine of between €6,500 and €25,000 (now between €5,792 and €23,169) would be imposed.
According to the Ministry, in Poland and Austria, up to 25 thousand people are awarded for violating the legislation on product safety. a fine of euros (the minimum amount of the fine is not fixed), in Belgium - from 26 euros to 600 thousand. a fine of 155 euros in Romania - from 155 euros to a fine of 6 666 euros, in Bulgaria - from 125 euros to a fine of 7 500 euros.
